Lifetimes are compile-time annotations that tell the compiler how long references are valid. They prevent dangling references (accessing freed memory).

Lifetimes are required when the compiler cannot determine the relationship between input and output references. For example:

fn longest<'a>(x: &'a str, y: &'a str) -> &'a str {
    if x.len() > y.len() { x } else { y }
}

Here, 'a tells the compiler the returned reference lives at least as long as both inputs. Without annotations, the compiler cannot know if the return value comes from x or y, so it cannot verify safety.

Most lifetimes are inferred by lifetime elision rules. You only annotate when the compiler cannot figure it out.
